<title>CTO : Statism</title><link rel="alternate" type="application/rss+xml" title="Recent Changes" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404/http://cliki.tunes.org/recent-changes.rdf"><link rel="stylesheet" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404cs_/http://cliki.tunes.org/admin/cliki.css"></head><body><div id="banner"><a title="CTO" class="logo" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404/http://cliki.tunes.org/">CTO</a> <span>CLiki for the TUNES project</span></div><div id="navbar"><a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404/http://cliki.tunes.org/index">Home</a> <a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404/http://cliki.tunes.org/Recent%20Changes">Recent Changes</a> <a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404/http://cliki.tunes.org/CLiki">About CLiki</a> <a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404/http://cliki.tunes.org/Text%20Formatting">Text Formatting</a> <a class="internal" onclick="if(name=window.prompt('New page name ([A-Za-z0-9 ])')) document.location='https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404/http://cliki.tunes.org/edit/'+name ;return false;" href="/web/20050416153404/http://cliki.tunes.org/">Create New Page</a></div><div id="main"><h1>Statism</h1>The <a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404/http://cliki.tunes.org/term">term</a> for the notion that the world is essentially <a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404/http://cliki.tunes.org/static">static</a>, that is, doesn't change significantly.

<p>Though statism may be locally valid (by definition of locality!), and thus helpful when measuring <a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404/http://cliki.tunes.org/expediency">expediency</a>, it is generally completely false in the long run and thus harmful when measuring real <a class="internal" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404/http://cliki.tunes.org/utility">utility</a>. 

<p><hr>
Wouldn't that be "staticism"?  Statism is the "concentration of economic controls and planning in the hands of a highly centralized government" (<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20050416153404/http://m-w.com/cgi-bin/dictionary?book=Dictionary&amp;va=Statism">m-w.com</a>), a widely used and known term.  This has nothing to do with that...

